## General

- Less is more. Prefer conciseness over verbosity -- LLMs generate faster than humans can keep up, so aim for good outlining that helps quick parsing and grokking as well as easy digestibility.
- Show your work, but keep it concise and useful.

## Code Quality & Style

- Follow codebase or relevant community conventions and style (eg, Python has [PEP-0008](https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/) and [Zen of Python](https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-Zen-of-Python)), but, in the absence of clear convention, then use the following personal inspirations and preferences as the default:
    - [YAGNI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/You_aren%27t_gonna_need_it)
    - [SOLID](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SOLID)
        - [Single responsibility principle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single-responsibility_principle)
    - [Separation of Concerns](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separation_of_concerns)
    - [UNIX Philosophy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_philosophy)
    - [The Pragmatic Programmer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Pragmatic_Programmer)
        - Tracer bullets
        - Fix broken windows
    - [Functional Programming Paradigm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_programming) -- especially the pragmatism of OCaml and F#.
    - Spaces > Tabs
    - Neovim > Vim > Emacs
    - Snake Case > Camel Case
    - Clean Code, but not Java
        - Comments as code unless explaining a decision or including references.
        - No dead code
    - [Avoid Hungarian Notation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hungarian_notation)
    - [The Zen of Python, by Tim Peters](https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-Zen-of-Python)
        - Beautiful is better than ugly.
        - Explicit is better than implicit.
        - Simple is better than complex.
        - Complex is better than complicated.
        - Flat is better than nested.
        - Sparse is better than dense.
        - Readability counts.
        - Special cases aren't special enough to break the rules.
        - Although practicality beats purity.
        - Errors should never pass silently.
        - Unless explicitly silenced.
        - In the face of ambiguity, refuse the temptation to guess.
        - There should be one-- and preferably only one --obvious way to do it.
        - Although that way may not be obvious at first unless you're Dutch.
        - Now is better than never.
        - Although never is often better than *right* now.
        - If the implementation is hard to explain, it's a bad idea.
        - If the implementation is easy to explain, it may be a good idea.
        - Namespaces are one honking great idea -- let's do more of those!
- Prefer early-exit guard clauses over nested/spaghetti control flow code.
- Never fail silently; fail loudly with a clear, actionable error.
- Keep logic flat and readable; avoid unnecessary inner helper functions.
- Prefer proven tools over hand-rolled scripts (eg, logrotate for log rotation) -- ideally lightweight tools.

## Version Control

- Follow [conventional commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/): use semantic commit subjects, and include audit-useful rationale/details in the commit body. Also see [Semantic Commit Messages](https://gist.github.com/joshbuchea/6f47e86d2510bce28f8e7f42ae84c7106).

## Context Compression/Compaction

- Always extract and share learnings that could be added to an `AGENTS.md` file before compacting.
